column11:
281673319 What version of jira are you running?

It's expecting Sprint data in the form of a raw toString due to how the api was returning the value. The Hygieia code works around this by attempting to reverse enginer that toString. If you are on a new version perhaps that bug has finally been fixed and it is correctly returning json.

281356452 @thashi  - #1130  is not using the encrypted password that resolved the issue. Remove encrypted password from the api.props, instead use actual db password and  use command 
==> java -jar api.jar --spring.config.location=api.properties 

if you want to use the encrypted password route - 
1) encrypt password using below command 
==> java -cp ~/.m2/repository/org/jasypt/jasypt/1.9.2/jasypt-1.9.2.jar  org.jasypt.intf.cli.JasyptPBEStringEncryptionCLI input="db password" password=hygieiasecret algorithm=PBEWithMD5AndDES

2) use the encrypted password in api.properties as 
   dbpassword=ENC(encrypted db password)
3) add "asypt.encryptor.password" = "hygieiasecret" as a environment variable 
4) Start api with below command 
==>java -jar api.jar --spring.config.location=api.properties -Djasypt.encryptor.password=hygieiasecret

 nireeshT
281419532 @thashi Is your prop file called application.properties  or dashboard.properties ?   Your comment has application.properties but your command references dashboard.properties.

java -jar api.jar --spring.config.location=dashboard.properties -Djasypt.encryptor.password=hygieiasecret

282013750 @avadhmr 2.0.5 supports Jenkins pipeline jobs, 2.0.4 does not. Your task is running as per the cron you have set. 0/5 min depending on how long a run takes. If you are trying to compare run times between 2.0.5 and 2.0.4, you need to make sure and empty your database so its a true comparison and not a delta. satishc1
282138560 @satishc1 both 2.0.5 and 2.0.4 are running on separate machines so I believe its a true comparison.
We are not running any pipeline jobs in our Jenkins so I don't think both the versions should take different times to collect the same data.

The major concern here is with 2.0.5, the collector is making insane amount of requests to the Production LDAP Server and thereby overloading it. Our LDAP team has requested us not to run the process because of it and hence we had to shut down the collector. This was not happening with 2.0.4 and only started with 2.0.5, that's why I think there is some issue with the recent changes done in it.

column2:
Create one team level dashboard, named teamDash1, then import build info and commit info of one project  to this dashboard, add this team level dashboard to a product level dashboard, the stages data of teamDash1 pipeline can be shown in the product level dashboard.
![teamdash1](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/15209842/23055955/d0e633be-f523-11e6-9997-d3eac596ee92.png)

But if I delete teamDash1, create a new teamDash2, and import the same data to it, the stages data of teamDash2 pipeline can't be shown in the product level dashboard. Why can't reuse the the stages data of teamDash1 pipeline?  How to reuse it?

If we can't reuse it because of some design reason, the teamDash1 pipeline is still in the database, it has not been deleted when teamDash1 deleted. And mybe the pipeline data will never be used, such dirty data should be deleted. 
![database](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/15209842/23055991/033754ce-f524-11e6-832a-493ebdc5d753.png)

At last, I think to reuse it is the best way.
column5: The stages data of one team dashboard pipeline can't be reused by another team level dashboard
column11:
280654204 It's a shortcoming of the current design. The pipeline is not filled with data until after it is created. #804

There is a hidden feature you can try by adding this to api.properties:

> feature.dynamicPipeline=enabled

It may need a few updates to work with the latest code. I have not had the time to update it yet. You can turn on debugging to see what it is doing. Basically the idea is to build the pipeline data on demand instead of building it when collectors run.

Here are my notes from a buried story on my backlog of things to do:
- Improve logging:
  - no commits found vs none in job
  - show full commit graph?
- Improve branch equality - origin/master vs master
- improve environment logging when a commit is not found (specify which environment)
- All commits vs bounded commits
- case sensitivity of component names vs artifact names
- Bug: the last commit in a graph is currently bound but we are adding their parent revision numbers into the commit graph. This results in an additional commit that we don't have knowledge of
- where does average of 35D come from for helloworld? MarkRx
282639717 I have debugged the dynamicPipeline feature, now I know how to produce pipeline stages data and how to show them.
(1). How to produce build stage data.
This feature will get only SCM info of the last build for one commit, then store it to the build stage. Why it don't collect all the build SCM info for one commit ?
(2). How to show commit stage data.
When get commit stage data from database, this feature will check build stage data first, if build stage data's scmRevisionNumber is same to commit stage data, commit stage data will be ignored and can't be shown. In my CI process, one commit automaticlly trigger one build, there will not be commit which has not been built, so the commit stage will always be blank, it can't show the average time of all the commits. 
I think don't ignore the commit data which have same scmRevisionNumber with build stage data is a better choice.
![commitstage](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/15209842/23351061/bd62ba64-fcf9-11e6-92d8-2cb186147acd.png)
 wdquan1985
282716895 You can't fill the SCM data from the build because not all of the necessary fields are available from the build collectors. That is why they are looked up. MarkRx
282977062  About the pipeline commit stage data.
 There are commit stage data in the database.
![pipedata](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/15209842/23397568/0b9d53f8-fdd4-11e6-81c2-99a2abb67a5d.png)
But the commit stage data can't be shown in the dashboard.
![commitnotshow](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/15209842/23397609/3aa678aa-fdd4-11e6-8a85-65ad8834ebea.png)
I have checked the code, and found the root cause, if build stage data's scmRevisionNumber is same to commit stage data, commit stage data can't be shown. so the commit stage will always be blank, it can't show the average time of all the commits. If I want to see the average time of commits, how to do it? wdquan1985
283085407 Yes I think that is the way the product view works right now (note it works they way regardless of the state of that feature switch). I agree that metrics should still show up even if no commits are in that exact stage. MarkRx
280577321 I have read the code, build stage data will be created only when the build info be saved to database, and this build stage data only belongs to one team level dashboard, the same to other stages. So if I create another team level dashboard, and import the same build data, build stage data will not be created for this new team level dashboard, because the build data will not be saved to database again.

And I know if there is new build info, it will be saved to build stage of the new team dashboard pipeline, but the past build info will not.
 wdquan1985

column11:
280655532 Correct. My team had discussed the idea of allowing arbitrary queries into the feature collection but we decided against it due to the complexity of having to support a query DSL. It would also require the collectors to have knowledge and be able to pull in arbitrary fields from the json response.

I do not have any plans to implement being able to support non-standard fields for teams. MarkRx
280715496 Thank you for answering my question. @MarkRx  tinabear
289809882 Closed. satishc1
325091000 Hi,Is there an update on this? Is there anyway to use team concept in Jira without using tempo-teams plugin? shabna96
325154245 @shabna96 Try this https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/pull/1644 satishc1
279810702 It does work without it. Use the latest codebase and remove the temp teams property MarkRx
279820802 Sorry, maybe i didn't express my question clearly.
I just want jira collector to show jira issues for different teams where tempo-team plugin is not installed. tinabear
279834388 @tinabear Do you have projects and teams configured in Jira without having the tempo-team plugin ? If you have a custom field defined for teams, you could set it for the property below and see if it works. Else set it to blank and the UI will assume team = Any.
```
#############################################################################
# In Jira, your instance will have its own custom field created for "team"
# This field allows you to specify that data field for your instance
# of Jira.  Note:  You can retrieve your instance's team ID field name via the following URI where your
# queried user story issue has team set on it; your custom field name describes the
# team value you expect to see:

280655532 Correct. My team had discussed the idea of allowing arbitrary queries into the feature collection but we decided against it due to the complexity of having to support a query DSL. It would also require the collectors to have knowledge and be able to pull in arbitrary fields from the json response.

I do not have any plans to implement being able to support non-standard fields for teams. MarkRx

This PR adds a link to the Sonar instance for the project as determined by the collector.

column2:
Using Hygieia as one tool across your enterprise for single view into your env, you can measure your progress for SDLC for your projects projects hosted on GIT. Metrics for Pulls and Issues can be added to the commits graph to show how the Pull Requests( code contributions) and Issues (ideas that help shape your project) are flowing in - and counts of developers committing, requesting a Pull and creating issues - would help us understand how popular your repo is.

Once the collector runs scanning GIT for all Pulls and Issues along with Commits as it does currently, it leaves the entries for the developers LOB/Department heads etc as TBD items so you can implement a local collector for your enterprise that scans for these and updates the fields by accessing your â€œHRâ€ data sources.

Code changes required would include API, githubcollector and UI.
column5: Add Pulls and Issues to Commits widget

column2:
We found a bug in the gitlab collector that would stop you from being able to get commits if the collector ran for a repo, but the collector was misconfigured.  What would happen is the collector would have a bad configuration that didn't allow you to retrieve commits from git.  If someone then created a Gitlab repo in a dashboard, the collector would run, retrieve no commits, and set the last updated to the current time.  The "first run" would have been run already.  Then, when the configuration was fixed, the collector would have already done the first run, so it would only try to retrieve commits from the "last update" time, back 10 minutes.  Therefor never retrieving the commits from whatever value was specified for first run.  This change prevents updating the "last update" time on a repo unless there was a successful request made to gitlab.  Any HttpClientErrorException or ResourceAccessException will prevent the "last update" time from changing, which means, a newly configured repo will get it's first run again, and other repos will get all commits from the last successful run.  

Sorry for the long explanation, I think there is probably more explanation than actual code.  Let me know if you have questions.

column2:
Review https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/issues/1116 for initial thoughts regarding this PR.
***Commits have been squashed for convenience.***

* The create dashboard modal has been expanded to allow selection of widgets from all 3 panes (1 below). 
* Update modal has been added to reselect which widgets the owner/admin wants to display (2 below).
* Configure icon has been added next to pane button set to allow for updates. This window can be expanded later to support extra dashboard specific configurations (3 below).
* Update is only available to owner/admin.
* Preexisting dashboards start with all widgets selected to support backwards compatibility, extraneous widgets can be removed by owner/admin.
* If no widgets are selected to be shown for a given pane, a helpful message appears explaining to any users wondering why no widgets are displayed.
* Template variable has been **removed** from the dashboard object, dashboard now maintains a map of available widget types and the panes where those widgets will be found.
* All template views have been consolidated into one single 'team.html/js' view. 

**Note** This PR allows users to select which widgets are displayed, it does not allow for multiple widgets of the same type. IE, having 2 Repository widgets is not supported.

**Example Screens**

1
![screen shot 2017-02-02 at 1 16 11 pm](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/20029463/22566590/de7849b2-e949-11e6-85b3-4cf3366c8c96.png)

column2:
As we rollout Hygieia throughout our organization, we find ourselves having to update property files to account for Jenkins or Sonar servers to pull data from, and restart corresponding applications. 

This enhancement enables maintaining this list of servers in a git repository (external from the application) and have Hygieia always pull the latest list of servers in every run without having to do any restart.

I do know there are other collectors that could take advantage of the collector-config-server. I first want to see if there's interest in this enhancement. If so, I could either apply it to the other collectors or have the community consume the collector-config-server as needed. I'm cool with either approach.

Hi Satish,

The solution given to https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/issues/1131 did not work. Hence creating a new issue since #1131 was closed.

This is what I did:

1. Stopped the collector.
2. Updated the existing dashboard with blank credentials and restarted the collector.
3. Performed a commit - but it was not picked up by the collector.
4. Stopped the collector.
5. Created a new dashboard with blank credentials and restarted the collector.
6. It picked up the commit performed in step#3 above.
7. Performed a new commit - but again this was not picked up by the collector.

Regards,
Rohan

276126925 @rohanb3 I'm assuming you are not getting any errors in your collector now that you've blanked your credentials out.

Now the commits will get picked as per your desired cron setting. You've set this to 
github.cron=0 0/5 * * * *

Leave the collector running (don't keep resetting it) for a 2 hour period (and do some commits in this time period) and see how the commits get collected based on your cron setting and refer to this to change this setting. http://docs.spring.io/spring-framework/docs/current/javadoc-api/org/springframework/scheduling/support/CronSequenceGenerator.html

Check your collector log for the 2 hour period. You should either see errors or you should see commits fetched based on your cron setting. satishc1

column2:
Resolves #1031. This was considerably bigger than @brennanananan and I had realized going in, but we feel like we have it at a really good spot. Test it out and let us know if there are any changes you would like to see or issues we need to address.  We are anticipating plenty of questions due to the nature of the pull request and it's size. 

**What's Included**
- Implemented JWT to provide stateless authentication/authorization
- Updated angular client to work with JWT tokens
- Made token expiration configurable
- Implemented redirect functionality to take you to the page you were viewing if you token expires and the API returns a 401 status code
- Made secret key configurable to support having multiple instances of the API running
- Added Spring Security to Rest API
- Built in support for multiple forms of authentication (standard and ldap auth currently implemented)
- Refactored current login to work with Spring Security
- Created a UserInfo Repository separate from the Authentication repository to support multiple forms of authentication. This lets us control all application specific details of a user such as roles and themes independent of the authentication type. (Themes are still only handled by the angular app on the client, and saved in local storage, but this is something we can now save for a user if we want to)
- Made admin a "role" instead of just assigning admin privileges to the user named "admin". (Haven't implemented a way to assign new admins yet, so right now it works as before where the user named "admin" is given the role of admin, this is handled on the backend.  There is no way to give an ldap user "admin" privileges currently unless their name is actually "admin")
- Added method level security to dashboard modification controller so only owners of the dashboard or admins can modify a dashboard
- Added support for having multiple owners of a dashboard (have not created anyway to assign multiple owners yet, but shouldn't be hard to do)
- Implemented new owner functionality in such a way that it won't break backwards compatibility

column2:
I am hoping someone can me out.  I think I am missing something very basic.  

I have Hygieia set up on a system and can run each piece correctly using the gulp
serve.  This means the API comes and connects to mongod and the UI launches under
gulp and I can access the dashboard through the UI interface.   I have been asked to
get the UI up under Tomcat rather than gulp serve.  To do this I set up Tomcat on the
same system, changed the port to 8090 so it did not conflict with the API Tomcat instance
and then moved the UI dist folder under the Tomcat webapps folder (and renamed it to
Hygieia).  Now, if I access Tomcat on that system and tell it specifically to bring up Hygieia .....
                                        localhost:8090/Hygieia
the login page appears but the API Connectivity shows no connection.

I have seen that in the gulpfile.js file, a proxy is set up to point to localhost:8080 where the 
instance of the API Tomcat would be.  I thought that is what I need to add to the start up of 
my instance of Tomcat but so far everything I have tried (adding proxy elements to both the
catalina.sh and to the JAVA_OPT in the catalina.properties files) does not work. 

I have looked through numerous other posts to try and find nuggets that I might be able
to look into to help me crack this nut - one post asked the submitter for the UI log files.  I
have not been able to find these on my system and I am pretty sure they might provide
some insight.

At this point I am thinking I am making this much more difficult than it has to be.  Any help
that anyone might be able to provide would be greatly appreciated.
column5: Problems getting Hygieia UI under Tomcat to connect to API
column11:
275782796 @amayesthing 

You are welcome! Here it is..

1. Build the Hygieia API project as a WAR artifact instead of JAR. i.e, Change the packaging to war in API project pom.xml, like below:
`<packaging>war</packaging>`
and re-build the API project.

2. Deploy the api*.war file in Tomcat.

3. Hygieia API requires the "dashboard.properties" file for MongoDB connectivity. To set this up with in Tomcat container, do the following:
       - Add a CATALINA_OPTS variable in Catalina.bat (or. sh under Linux) file like below (update the path based on your environment):
         `set CATALINA_OPTS="-Dspring.config.location=file:C:\DevOps\HygieiaApi\dashboard.properties"`

   Note : I added the above variable right below this line:
           :java_dir_displayed
           echo Using CLASSPATH:       "%CLASSPATH%"
           set CATALINA_OPTS="-Dspring.config.location=file:C:\DevOps\HygieiaApi\dashboard.properties"

Restart your Tomcat server. You should be able to run the UI that should connect to your API deployed within Tomcat successfully. Try it out!

 spyndi
276096582 @spyndi thanks. satishc1
276190542 Thanks @spyndi - I appreciate your help - I have not tried this yet but it looks straight forward to me and I think it will resolve our problem.  Thank you for closing this issue. amayesthing

I had looked into that because the issue that I cited above referring to the UI log files #1019 also requested details on the connection in the httpd conf.  I appreciate your suggestion and will take it back to the team to see if that would meet everyone's needs.  I would like to keep this open until I get concurrence from the team just in case anyone has a clever way to get it working under Tomcat.  Thanks again. amayesthing

I got this working by deploying the Hygieia API within the Tomcat container. Basically, the UI and the API are deployed within Tomcat and all the collectors are running as a stand-alone java processes. It works good and also provides an opportunity to scale-up & load balance APIs, if needed.

Let me know if you are interested in this deployment, I can document the changes (2 changes) and will send it out to you. spyndi

Hi,

We have Rally which is SSO integrated and this is identity provider initiated. In which case Rally URL would not work due to IDP redirection. How does one generate security token in such scenarios to be used with REST APIs inside collector?

Thanks,
Booma Baskaran.
column11:
458147599 I have the same issue, can you please let me know, if there is any update. Naveenraaj
458178128 If I'm understanding the question here, you have SSO login in front of your tools (e.g. Jira) and you want the collector to get past this. The answer will depend on the specific tool.

For example, in the case of the Jira collector, you can generate a token and use that in place of a password. In the case of SonarQube collector, a generated token stands in for the username and no password is required.

Your best bet is to refer to the docs for your product. spyoungtech
458182855 @spyoungtech

I'm having this case with rally, is there a way to handle it in rally collector. Naveenraaj
458391720 Sorry, I'm not familiar with rally. I would suggest referring to the product documentation. 

A [quick search](https://communities.ca.com/thread/241782087-sso-saml-api-authorization) seems to indicate that an API shouldn't require SAML/SSO auth. Additionally, it seems that you can add exceptions for specific users, say, for example a service account.

Maybe someone with more knowledge of this product can help. spyoungtech

I want to know if there is any possible way for aggregating various modules which form one complete application.
In our case we have application divided into multiple independent components having separate git repos, jenkins jobs , sonar projects etc.

Also any future plans of having a collector for CA release automation deployment tool?

column2:
Hello

Currently Hygieia allows the user to select a "template" from a hard coded list (capone, caponechatops, splitview, etc). The purpose from what I can tell (please correct me in the comments if I am wrong) is merely to change which widgets are displayed on initial dashboard creation. At this point there does not exist a way to easily create, modify, or delete these templates. 

My proposal is to remove the notion of these templates, and allow the users to select which widgets they would like to be displayed during the dashboard creation configuration window.

![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/20029463/22209899/43d351b0-e145-11e6-8ee1-6233ab482f03.png)

The screenshot is a POC for the widgets on the "Widget" tab only. The change can easily be propagated to the "Pipeline" and "Cloud" tabs as well. In the case the all widgets are excluded, the tab will not show. For example, on the screen shot above, if all widgets are deselected, the "Widget" tab on the actual dashboard will be removed.

On a similar note, if a user decides that they would like all of the widgets shown in the example, the dashboard becomes too large to fit in one screen. Having a page that requires scrolling for an application like this may become cumbersome for users. 
Two solutions have been suggested for this:
* Limit the amount of widgets in a dashboard.
* If the page requires scrolling, have the page slowly move up and down automatically to show all widgets.

Both approaches have merit, please let me know if there is feedback.

This change would allow teams to show precisely the information they desire, and would result in a cleaner looking dashboard instance in the case that a team does not want to utilize all widgets included in a pre-baked template.

Looking forward, this change incorporates adding widgets directly to the dashboard object itself. This can be utilized in the future to allow addition/deletion of widgets to pre-exiting dashboards.

273959690 yes..we were earlier using old UI...but now we have switched to latest one from master(we switched to latest once started facing these issues). But As I said everything seems to be running fine...just that am bit unsure about the startup error avadhmr
274087170 The cause of the null pointer is this: API call is made to retrieve a dashboard, but the dashboard is not there in the "dashboard" collection in Mongo. If you have removed the data from Mongo, I am thinking (a) there is some other browser instance still trying to pull up an old dashboard or (2) Your browser has the URL in the history and you are using that as a bookmark and that creates the error. 

Other than those, I cant think of anything else. Would like to see it in a screen share if possible.  tabladrum
274113025 Having said that, the API should return a 404 in this case. tabladrum

column2:
I'm trying to get Hygieia running in containers with Openshift. 

I have three separate pods: mongo, api, ui. The api layer is able to communicate with the mongo pod. 

The UI layer is running, but not able to connect to the api layer. In my Chrome browser console, I see this error:

> XMLHttpRequest cannot load http://api-hygieia.apps.cluster.local/api/dashboard. No 'Access-Control-Allow-Origin' header is present on the requested resource. Origin 'http://ui-hygieia.apps.cluster.local' is therefore not allowed access.

When I add the cross-origin resource sharing extension to my browser, they are able to connect. 

Is there a better solution for this so all users won't have to add the extension?
column5: Cross-origin resource sharing error between api and ui
column11:
274180462 @amitmawkin please see. tabladrum
276089567 Update: I was able to find a solution to this CORS filter issue.

By adding these four lines of code into the LoggingFilter.java file and running the maven build on the api layer, cross origin domains are accepted.

`httpServletResponse.addHeader("Access-Control-Allow-Origin", "*");
httpServletResponse.addHeader("Access-Control-Allow-Methods", "GET, POST, PUT, DELETE");			httpServletResponse.addHeader("Access-Control-Allow-Headers", "Content-Type");
httpServletResponse.addHeader("Access-Control-Max-Age", "1");`

I'll be adding a pull request for this so others can avoid this issue. jshpopelka272

274205649 Works with freestyle as well as pipeline. For freestyle, configure Hygiea publisher as post build action and select to publish deploy data. You will need an App Name to publish under (this is the one you will select in Hygieia deploy widget config drop down), an env name (whatever you want such as Dev, QA, Prod etc), a namespace, select which artifacts are being deployed (files under your workspace, supports wildcard) and optionally version number. Supply version number if the filename does not contain version number.  tabladrum

column2:
I was getting a 401 unauthorized error with the Bitbucket collector. After doing more research, it appears the issue is due to a special character (#) in the password used.

I placed an additional log.debug statement in the DefaultBitbucketServerClient, right after the password decryption: decryptedPassword = Encryption.decryptString(repo.getPassword(), settings.getKey());

password: testpass#
```
2017-01-14 00:50:01,991 DEBUG c.c.d.collector.GitCollectorTask - {password=UKlOFa2bOkMoAJSkMI26bw==, scm=Bitbucket, branch=master, userID=testuser, url=https://git-qa.******.net/scm/devops/testhygieia.git}::master
2017-01-14 00:50:01,992 DEBUG c.c.d.c.DefaultBitbucketServerClient - Rest Url: https://git-qa.******.net/rest/api/1.0/projects/devops/repos/testhygieia/commits?until=master&limit=25
2017-01-14 00:50:01,994 DEBUG c.c.d.c.DefaultBitbucketServerClient - decryptedPassword: testpass
```
As you can see, the '#' is missing.

column11:
272600277 Thanks for the quick response. Once I restarted my machine in order to gather the information you requested, the SCM widget accepted the password successfully without having to modify anything. Although I had restarted the processes several times today, it seems restarting my machine did the trick. I do see the credentials with an encrypted password in the database as well. Unfortunately, I'm getting '401 Unauthorized' from the Bitbucket collector when it attempts to retrieve commits from the repository. I'll do more research to see if I can identify the issue. Thanks again. rdsteele
272603765 I was able to get the Bitbucket collector to work finally, but I did find an issue. The password I was using had a special character (#) which caused a problem with the encrypt/decrypt function. Once I switched to an alphanumeric password, the decryption worked and I was able to obtain the commit information. I'll open a new issue once I gather more information. Thanks again. rdsteele
273561935 @rdsteele @satishc1 - I followed the steps for generating the secret key and updated the same in 
api properties file as well as bitbucket properties file but still getting the same error. 

I also changed the password to only contain alphanumeric but still getting the same encryption error. Could you please provide the detailed steps to resolve this issue?

Thanks for your help in advance. asub927
273865733 So, my understanding is the password encryption error in the UI SCM widget configuration was solved by generating the secret key and adding that to the API properties file as 'key=secretkeyvalue'. This should allow the API to encrypt the password and store the credentials in the database. I also restarted my machine; stopping and starting the API process didn't seem to work for some reason, not sure why.

1. java -jar core-2.0.5-SNAPSHOT.jar com.capitalone.dashboard.util.Encryption
    Your secret key is:
    NH***************************TC

2. Property added to api.properties (or whatever your file is named)
    key=NH********************************TC

Adding the secret key to the Bitbucket properties allows the collector to read the encrypted password from the database, decrypt it and call Bitbucket. If this fails, you'll probably be getting a 401 Unathorized error, which is how I discovered the issue with the '#' special character.

3. Property added to Bitbucket git.properties  (or whatever your file is named)
    git.key=NH********************************TC

275200782 @shilpsl1 @tabladrum 
FYI - We are also using UCD 6.2.1 version and running into the same issue as reported above.

@tabladrum - I was doing some debugging with the UDeploy collector code and may have some additional data for troubleshooting.

I see that the method "getLowestLevelChildren" in DefaultUDeployClient class is returning a null JSONArray and hence the subsequent calls in the stack is not collecting any data for the widget.

`private JSONArray getLowestLevelChildren(JSONObject topParent, JSONArray returnArray) {
        JSONArray jsonChildren = (JSONArray) topParent.get("children");

        if (jsonChildren != null && jsonChildren.size() > 0) {
            for (Object child : jsonChildren) {
                if (!hasChildren((JSONObject) child)) {
                    returnArray.add(child);
                } else {
                    getLowestLevelChildren((JSONObject) child, returnArray);
                }
            }
        }
        return returnArray;
    }`

The input JSONObject to this method is -

{"parent":{"inheritTeam":false,"active":true,"description":"Test - Application","prototype":false,"tags":[],"impersonationForce":false,"path":"\/test-103831","security":{"Delete":false,"Manage Impersonation":false,"Manage Teams":false,"Edit Basic Settings":false,"read":false,"Map to Environments":false,"View Resources":false,"write":false,"Manage Children":false,"Create Resources":false,"Manage Properties":false},"hasAgent":false,"name":"test-103831","impersonationPassword":"****","securityResourceId":"d346ec32-9622-4364-92d2-4938617ca6bc","id":"f3c72817-394e-48f5-8e4a-f314816a61f6","impersonationUseSudo":false,"discoveryFailed":false},"isRoot":true,"inheritTeam":true,"resource":{"id":"c0d838a4-fe9a-4533-a0b1-33c87629a701"},"hasChildren":true,"active":true,"description":"CIT2","type":"subresource","prototype":false,"tags":[],"impersonationForce":false,"path":"\/test-103831\/CIT2","security":{"Delete":false,"Manage Impersonation":false,"Manage Teams":false,"Edit Basic Settings":false,"read":true,"Map to Environments":false,"View Resources":true,"write":false,"Manage Children":false,"Create Resources":false,"Manage Properties":false},"hasAgent":false,"versions":[],"name":"CIT2","impersonationPassword":"****","securityResourceId":"c0d838a4-fe9a-4533-a0b1-33c87629a701","id":"301b972c-668e-4b9a-a0b0-4c9814889b40","impersonationUseSudo":false,"discoveryFailed":false}

In short, I don't see a "children" node or tag in this JSON construct. I wonder if there is an API/Response change between UCD 6.1.x and 6.2.x is the root cause of this issue.

BTW, the "getLowestLevelChildren" method is being called from "getEnvironmentResourceStatusData" method and I see a comment about some "new logic" that was introduced on Dec16/2015. Please check.

If you would like me to step through the code via. Webex let me know, we can schedule some time.
 spyndi

column11:
271286299 Nope. Perhaps #1031 will address that.

@rob-miller-777  MarkRx
271295343 Correct @MarkRx, we will be making admin a "role", so you can have multiple admin accounts.  We do not intend on adding functionality to add new admins with #1031 however, we felt that was beyond the scope of the pull request.  We just wanted to get it back to the current state with backend security.  We did lay the groundwork to make it possible though.   rob-miller-777
272893811 @vetrivelan25 Not at this time. satishc1

column2: This harvests the enhancements in PR https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/pull/1049 and switches the config UI on both Jenkins and Sonar (widgets that deal with a massive data set) from ui-select to  an input with uib-typeahead, returning 20 results at a time. In order to use uib-typeahead, upgrading to the latest stable release of Angular (1.5.9) and latest version of UI-Bootstrap (2.3.0) were necessary.

276963572 @satishc1 below is a screenshot of how configuring jenkins or sonar looks like with this enhancement. 

The way we (@rob-miller-777 and I) have it configured is:

- on click to the search field without typing anything, it will send a server side request without any search criteria but the size of 20 
`api/collector/item/type/build?size=20`
- with the screenshot I provided below I typed in 'BusinessLine' as a search criteria. As I was typing this, the following server side requests were made:
`api/collector/item/type/build?search=Busines&size=20`
`api/collector/item/type/build?search=Business&size=20`
`api/collector/item/type/build?search=BusinessLine&size=20`
  This is so, because we've configured the search text field with a 250 ms of typeahead-wait-ms. Typeahead-wait-ms (from angular docs) is the minimal wait time after last character typed before typeahead kicks-in.

The idea is for users to type in what they are searching for and if the result they are looking for doesn't show up on the first 20 results, continue to refine the results by typing more.

Let me know if you need further details. Thanks.

![buildwidget_configure](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/13173260/22551218/29655cbe-e911-11e6-9219-8eaaeb0e9260.png)
 Mpluya
277287732 @Mpluya @rob-miller-777 @mdskd @tabladrum Thanks for the screenshot and the details. If the results are being paginated, there should be a prev and next button to browse the "pages". The user will not know why their "desired" result is not showing up in the first 20 or whatever number we set. While this is a great feature we really need it, can you explore the possibility of adding a way to browse through the search results ? Your thoughts ? satishc1
277299120 Yeah, I think it could benefit from some sort of infinite scroll.  I think we had looked into that, but finding a library that could handle the filtering and infinite scroll was challenging.  We could take a look again however.   rob-miller-777
277325841 agree with comments that some sort of paging in the ui would be good - infinite scroll fits more in this particular scenario from a ui design perspective.


Let take a look at this next week @rob-miller-777 mdavis40
278082914 @satishc1 @tabladrum We have been trying a few different things to utilize pagination.  Our first attempt was to add infinite scroll to the UIB-Typeahead directive.  This doesn't seem to be possible without either modifying the source code for the typeahead directive, or creating our own.  Neither of which seem ideal to us.  We also couldn't find any existing libraries that combine infinite scroll/pagination and filtering in a select dialog.  We are currently trying a different approach by adding a table/list of "jobs" to the form, and server side pagination and filtering on top of that.  The functionality is much easier to implement for this, however the user experience suffers a little bit as it takes up more of the screen, and there are more buttons to click for navigating.  So the two options we are looking at right now are keeping the functionality as is in this merge request, where to find your job, you have to continue to type your job name until it appears in the list.  Or we can add the table with filtering and pagination.  We will submit a merge request with the second option when ready. rob-miller-777
278103097 @rob-miller-777 @tabladrum  If the UIB-typeahead paginated scrolling is tough to implement, then given a choice between the 2 options, I would pick option 1. We can have a quick conference call if you have some time available. We are on gitter.im, if you wanna ping me at a convenient time. Thanks for researching this. satishc1

column2: We ran into a scenario where one of our users created a dashboard with a slash ('/') in the name, i.e. "Test/Dashboard". While dashboard creation was successful, he then was unable to configure any of the widgets. This is so because the configure action was unable to hit the '/dashboard/myowner/{dashboardtitle}' endpoint, since his request was '/dashboard/myowner/Test/Dashboard'. My question to the group is, would there be interest in adding a validation around the dashboard name to prevent slashes and or any special characters? If yes, I'll open a PR on this. Thanks.

277276431 @abhishekvats007 The feature widget now has an option to display metrics based on the number of tickets instead of estimates. This is for setups that do not use estimates.
Functionality merged in https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/pull/1054 Use latest codebase. Youâ€™ll also need to follow cleanup instructions provided in https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/pull/1137 satishc1

column11: 363171299 @urbaitel - the compose file included in the repo is intended to be for getting a local setup running. It references the images on your local machine which are made available after running `mvn clean install docker:build`. We currently don't keep the images in Docker Hub updated but we intend to do so in the near future. In the meantime you can run the above command to generate the images and from there you can push the images anywhere you'd like.  matthewbeasley

270018620 After reading the thread, I think I follow... Would it make more sense for the collector to record the deployment server as a compound key? i.e. ```json [ { "applicationId": "MyTestApp", "deployServer": "TestJenkins" }, { "applicationId": "MySecondApp", "deployServer": "TestJenkins" }, { "applicationId": "AnotherTestApp", "deployServer": "TestJenkins" } ] ``` I'm not sure exactly what the data looks like that the widget is displaying or if I completely understand the problem, but this data model would make it possible to group/aggregate by deploy server, as proposed. mrpudn 270125129 @mrpudn changing the collectors / collector_items around would be a big undertaking and would most certainly not be backwards compatible. @tabladrum Looks fine so long as the same guid implies the same name (meaning we don't care about renaming). Just note I don't see the api endpoint I made going away as there are more uses for it. For example: Configurable Pipeline Stage Names #1020 MarkRx 270130185 @MarkRx The "System Config" API should evolve. For this particular instance we will rely on the UI config ability. tabladrum 270131578 Sounds good. MarkRx 270150077 https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/pull/1055 tabladrum 269544000 Do the created collector items have unique options.applicationId's? Can you post them? The assumption would be that "MyTestApp", "MySecondApp", and "AnotherTestApp" would each have their own unique applicationId. If not then they will be treated as the same application if they all have the same instanceUrl (and thus assume they have the same application name for all 3 which is why the first name is used in the group) ``` var dataGrouped = dataGrouped = _(data) .groupBy(function(d) { return (!multiServerEquality ? d.options.instanceUrl + "#" : "" ) + d.options.applicationId; }) .map(function(d) { return d; }); ``` MarkRx 269547708 Ah. Got it. In my case (testing jenkins plugin) I had the same instanceUrl. And no applicationId in the collector item option. May be the workaround is to put Job url in the "instanceUrl". Not sure yet. But manually editing the json document to make the instance url the job url did work. Noticed that if I turn the grouping off, it still groups. tabladrum 269574464 @MarkRx the following code should work both ways: ``` var dataGrouped = _(data) .groupBy(function(d) { return (!multiServerEquality || d.options.applicationId == null ? d.options.instanceUrl + "#"+d.options.applicationName : "" ) + d.options.applicationId; }) .map(function(d) { return d; }); ``` Can you test this change locally? tabladrum 269631174 I think the proper solution should be to have the jenkins plugin assign each application an applicationId. That field really shouldn't be nullable as it is meant to be an identifier. The identifier could be something arbitrary like the md5sum of the instanceUrl + applicationName. It's possible there are other parts of the code that will choke if it is null. Since a.applicationId == b.applicationId implies a.applicationName == b.applicationName you can use this: ``` var dataGrouped = dataGrouped = _(data) .groupBy(function(d) { return (!multiServerEquality ? d.options.instanceUrl + "#" : "" ) + d.options.applicationName + "#" + d.options.applicationId; }) .map(function(d) { return d; }); ``` MarkRx 269642107 The origin of applicationID was from uDeploy that had some kind of of UUID for each applicationID. I am sure this ID will change if the same App was setup in another "Prod" uDeploy server. May be we should create another ID (some kind of CMDB identifier)? In your case, how are you keeping this ID same across multiple deployment server? tabladrum 269650311 I kind of "cheated". XLD uses composite path keys based on the names of items in the path. Since this is the case the applicationId remains the same so long as they have the same path. For example: Server1: Id: Applications/Foo/Bar Name: Bar Server2: Id: Applications/Foo/Bar Name: Bar MarkRx 269986021 @MarkRx @amitmawkin @satishc1 @mrpudn please review these following change proposal before I submit it in a PR form: With PR https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/pull/891 there was a change in how deployed Apps were grouped together by "deploying server"s. Nice change. This allows to visualize an App deployment where different deployment servers (such as QA Jenkins, Prod Jenkins or whatever) are deploying the same app. There are two major changes in that PR: 1. New API for to return a boolean attribute (systemConfig.multipleDeploymentServers) to the API properties file that determines if servers need to be grouped. 2. UI changes to group the servers in https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/UI/src/components/widgets/deploy/config.js and https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/UI/src/components/widgets/deploy/config.html I am proposing a refactor of #1 and slight change to #2. **Slight Change to #2**: Instead of relying on non-null applicationId, I am proposing a non-null applicationName + applicationId check in grouping of elements: *Old code* (https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/UI/src/components/widgets/deploy/config.js) ``` var dataGrouped = _(data) .groupBy(function(d) { return (!multiServerEquality ? d.options.instanceUrl + "#" : "" ) + d.options.applicationId; }) .map(function(d) { return d; }); ``` *Proposed change* ``` var dataGrouped = _(data) .groupBy(function(d) { return (!multiServerEquality ? d.options.instanceUrl + "#" : "" ) + d.options.applicationName + d.options.applicationId; }) .map(function(d) { return d; }); ``` **Refactoring of #1** Instead of capturing/configuring the "multipleDeploymentServers" property via API, I am proposing that we do that in the UI and store each individual dashboard's choice in the "dashboard" document in dashboard -> widgets -> options section of the json document: ``` { "_id" : ObjectId("5863ed079220ab16e6a1c3c8"), "name" : "deploy", "componentId" : ObjectId("583394884969c83f6715b588"), "options" : { "id" : "deploy0", "aggregateServers" : true } }, ``` Corresponding UI changes are pretty simple. *Add a check box in deploy widget config:* ```
``` Add a new variables in the corresponding controller (config.js) and add a function that looks like this: ``` $scope.reload = function() { processResponse(ctrl.currentData); }; ``` And store the currentData in a global variable after the data is obtained from the API calls. With these changes, there will be no API needed to save/retrieve the config and the config is set for each individual dashboard. Thoughts? Hi,

we are trying to consume Jira, BitBucket, Jenkins and Sonar hosted behind a federations service (ADFS).  OAuth is also available. Do you offer any means to authenticate the collector so we can retrieve the data? Note that I do not want to federate the Hygieia Application it self, only the collectors (for now).

My HL architecture is described as follows: Collectors (running on AWS) -> DevOps Tools (running on Enterprise network, behind federation).
column11:
269225683 +1 oAuth pess0a
269366695 We have similar situations in some cases - meaning some tools (such as SVN for example) are in Enterprise Network. All you need (I think) is an admin level system account on those tools and your AWS security group allowing outbound traffic to your enterprise network.  tabladrum
269467376 @tabladrum the point is when the request gets to the enterprise reverse proxy it identifies the call as an unauthenticated one, and redirects the call to the federation authentication page. Once this is a collector request, there is no user to provide credentials, and the request fails.  All this happens before the collector request reach the destination tool. I was wondering if it is possible to provide user credentials to the collectors, so it can use the credential when requesting data. mmullerbr

column2:
When having a large amount of collector items for a specific collector type (10000 Jenkins Jobs for instance), it could take some extra time to send all of the items to the UI. This pull request allows the api to return paginated results. We also repurposed the 'collectorItemsByType' operation to allow for a search/filter functionality. This is backwards compatible with all widgets and is a non breaking change; the only changes to the response from the API are in the header dictating paging information. If no paging information is included in the request, all items are returned by default.

We will have PR's in the future that allow these widgets to have a 'typeahead' functionality that will dynamically load the field as you type, which utilize the changes made in this PR. This will all result in a significant performance increase and enhance user experience in the case of large collector item sets.

268987955 @pxk5958 is actually investigating this right now. We also have 10000's of Jenkins jobs and the build widget config in-particular is not very responsive. We have found two causes:

- The angular module ui-select has several well known performance problems. @pxk5958 was looking into using an alternative called selectize.
- For some reason spring is taking a long time to serialize the database results into objects. Results return quickly when using a mongo utility.

Does paging really help? I don't think the actual network load is an issue. You might be seeing a perceived increase in performance because the reduction in data addresses reduces the effects of both issues above.

268658328 How does the jenkins plugin handle multiple scms right now? Are we just using the first?

The metadata is needed. It wouldn't make sense for metadata to be a list as it is simply a key-value property holder (that corresponds to artifactory properties). Instead you could use a numbering scheme similar to how jenkins handles multiple repositories. Example:

```
scmUrl: "url",
scmUrl1: "url1",
scmUrl2: "url2"
scmBranch: "..."
scmBranch1: "..."
```

Since this has been the source of several issues, I think it best to disable browser-sync's [`ghostMode`](https://www.browsersync.io/docs/options/#option-ghostMode) feature, by default.

Ghost mode can be enabled by running `gulp serve:ghost-mode` if you require this functionality.

Resolves #1016

Now you should be able to do a `gulp serve` to get the UI started. mrpudn

268355391 Ah, sorry I just edited my previous post - it looks like you specified `-j` instead of `-g`. `-g` will install the node module globally, then you can use it on the command-line, i.e. `bower` and `gulp`.

After you get bower and gulp:
```
bower install
gulp serve
``` mrpudn

268311865 I resolved the issue.  Problem was in by .bowerrc file.  

I had following in the file:
```
{
  "directory": "library",
  "registry": "http://bower.herokuapp.com",
  "proxy": "[PROXY_SERVER_ADDRESS_:PORT_HERE]",
  "https-proxy": "[PROXY_SERVER_ADDRESS:PORT_HERE]"
}
```

When I changed to this:
```
{
  "proxy": "[PROXY_SERVER_ADDRESS_:PORT_HERE]",		
  "https-proxy": "[PROXY_SERVER_ADDRESS:PORT_HERE]"
}
```
It worked.

Thanks for pointing me in the right direction. Mark-Smithh
268323424 Ah, ok - glad to see you got it resolved.

As a side note - you shouldn't have to set the bower proxy settings explicitly like that. It should honor your `HTTP_PROXY` and `HTTPS_PROXY` environment variables, if you have them set. Most tools follow this convention, which makes things much easier behind a proxy. mrpudn

268311865 I resolved the issue.  Problem was in by .bowerrc file.  

I had following in the file:
```
{
  "directory": "library",
  "registry": "http://bower.herokuapp.com",
  "proxy": "[PROXY_SERVER_ADDRESS_:PORT_HERE]",
  "https-proxy": "[PROXY_SERVER_ADDRESS:PORT_HERE]"
}
```

When I changed to this:
```
{
  "proxy": "[PROXY_SERVER_ADDRESS_:PORT_HERE]",		
  "https-proxy": "[PROXY_SERVER_ADDRESS:PORT_HERE]"
}
```
It worked.

Thanks for pointing me in the right direction. Mark-Smithh
268323424 Ah, ok - glad to see you got it resolved.

As a side note - you shouldn't have to set the bower proxy settings explicitly like that. It should honor your `HTTP_PROXY` and `HTTPS_PROXY` environment variables, if you have them set. Most tools follow this convention, which makes things much easier behind a proxy. mrpudn

Adds support for Jenkins pipeline plugin. https://wiki.jenkins-ci.org/display/JENKINS/Pipeline+Plugin

Includes support for addons to the plugin such as the multi-branch pipeline. Child jobs show up as "parent/child". Note that a job will not show up without a build.

SVN was not tested but should work as there were no provider specific changes made.

column2: Problem: When the Jenkins collector runs and encounters a workflow type job ("_class":"org.jenkinsci.plugins.workflow.job.WorkflowRun"), the collector throws an exception since workflow type jobs don't have changeSets. This is a fix to add a null check and immediately exit from the method when there are no changeSets to build, but still allow to collect build information from a workflow job.
column5: changes to allow collecting builds from a workflow type jenkins job
column11:
267103536 Thanks @MarkRx  amitmawkin
267134415 Full support for jenkins pipeline plugin PR #1038 MarkRx
267160270 @amitmawkin this solves the error encountered on any workflow type job with just an addition of a null check. I probably should reword this request to instead say "handle null changeSet scenarios",
 which i happen to have encountered on workflow type jobs. Thanks. Mpluya
267167141 @Mpluya Workflow/Pipeline jobs have the changesets as a JSONArray of "changeSets" instead of "changeSet" in normal jobs. That's why you're encountering the NPE. With your change, it would skip the NPE, but will not collect the actual changesets if present. pxk5958
267204885 @pxk5958 I appreciate the explanation. Closing this request since PR #1038 addresses the entire need. Mpluya

Unfortunately, we still have a jira 5.1 instance running in the company with which I met a NullPointerException in Jira collector. I change the code locally to get it working with jira 5.1 api, currently.
Therefore, I am not sure do your team has the clear scope on what is the lowest supported version of Jira (mostly we're running 6+)?  

Plus to share the issue:
on the jira API  <jira-host>/rest/api/2/status: 
6.1+
```json
{
  "description": "The issue is open and ready for the assignee to start work on it.",
  "iconUrl": "http://xxx/images/icons/statuses/open.png",
  "id": "1",
  "name": "Open",
  "self": "http://xxx/rest/api/2/status/1",
  "statusCategory": {
    "colorName": "blue-gray",
    "id": 2,
    "key": "new",
    "name": "To Do",
    "self": "http://xxx/rest/api/2/statuscategory/2"
  }
}
```
5.1:
```json
{
  "description": "The issue is open and ready for the assignee to start work on it.",
  "iconUrl": "http://xxxx/images/icons/status_open.gif",
  "id": "1",
  "name": "Open",
  "self": "http://xxx/rest/api/2/status/1"
}
```
According to **Hygieia/collectors/feature/jira/src/main/java/com/capitalone/dashboard/client/DefaultJiraClient.java**, line [367-369]:
```java
Object statusCategory = jsonStatus.get("statusCategory");
JSONObject jsonStatusCategory = (JSONObject) statusCategory;
String statusCategoryName = (String) jsonStatusCategory.get("name");
```
Obviously, if I am running with jira 5.1 api, I will get a null statusCategory which leads to a NullPointerException when I afterwards try to get() from null :(

Currently I make the if statement after line 367 to judge with I get a null of 'statusCategory' to get everything working.

Please advice if you're support jira 5.1 .

Thanks,
Xiaopeng

Hi Team,
I am using the Hygieia Jenkins plugin to publish deployment details on Hygieia db but it is not clearly documented anywhere as how to and why to create different environments like Dev, Int, Perf in jenkins so that it will reflect on teams of Deploy widget configuration. Any clarification would be helpful. Thanks.
column5: No teams were found in Deploy widget of Hygieia db
column11:
268540175 @supremex1 You can create jobs in Jenkins that deploy to Dev , QA , Int , Perf , Prod.
In these jobs, under Post Build Actions -> Hygieia Publisher -> select "Publish Build Status" and  "Publish Deployment Results" and fill in the details of your artifact. The environment name will be set to one of Dev , QA , Int , Perf , Prod.  Then run these jobs and you should see the deploy widget populated. satishc1

268521095 There is no field called feature.jiraProjectID. I do not know where that came from.

Jira does not have a user role system. The jira collector will pick up whatever the user has access to that is defined in the jira collector properties. Creating such a system is no small task and I don't see it being done any time soon if at all. MarkRx

column2: We have been looking into the security in Hygieia and have some concerns with how itâ€™s implemented. Â It looks like there is a call to the API service to login, but after that, all the authorization is in javascript and based on a couple cookies. Â Security can be bypassed completely with very little effort. Â Is there any work being done to address this? If not, we might look into improving this.

270969656 Hey guys, just wanted to provide an update.  @brennanananan and I have put a lot of work into implementing security, and we are getting close to having it where we want.  From a users perspective, almost nothing has changed.  But the application is secure from the backend now.

**What we have done so far**
- Implemented JWT to provide stateless authentication/authorization
- Updated angular client to work with JWT tokens
- Made token expiration configurable
- Implemented redirect functionality to take you to the page you were viewing if you token expires and you have to login again
- Made secret key configurable to support having multiple instances of the API running
- Added Spring Security to Rest API
- Built in support for multiple forms of authentication (only standard Hygieia Auth implemented at this point, but adding others should be easy)
- Refactored current login to work with Spring Security
- Created a UserInfo Repository separate from the Authentication repository to support multiple forms of authentication.  This lets us control all application specific details of a user such as roles and themes independent of the authentication type. (Themes are still only handled by the angular app on the client, and saved in local storage, but this is something we can now save for a user if we want to)
- Made admin a "role" instead of just assigning admin privileges to the user named "admin". (Haven't implemented a way to assign new admins yet, so right now it works as before where the user named "admin" is given the role of admin)
- Added method level security to dashboard modification controller so only owners of the dashboard or admins can modify a dashboard
- Added support for having multiple owners of a dashboard (have not created anyway to assign multiple owners yet, but shouldn't be hard to do)
- Implemented new owner functionality in such a way that it won't break backwards compatibility

**What we have left**

- Clean up and refactor code
- Add and update some unit tests
- Document what we have done and how things work
- Document how to add additional forms of authentication (oauth, ldap, etc...)

Here is a link to the diff if you want to take a look at what we have so far: https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/compare/master...StateFarmIns:springSecurityIntegration

Let us know if you have any questions or concerns on what we have, should have a pull request coming shortly.  
 rob-miller-777

276388451 The "attemptAuthentication" method in the LdapLoginRequestFilter is responsible for pulling the username and password out of the request, and creating a "UsernamePasswordAuthenticationToken" which will be handled by Spring Securities built in LDAP authentication provider.  From the issues you are having it seems like there are probably two potential issues you could be facing.  The first would be an improperly configured ldap server, most likely your DN string not being accurate. 268522270 To show scrum sprints you must (1) have the collector property configured, and (2) have a project/team have an active ending sprint. If a sprint exists but has no end date it will be treated as a kanban sprint.
@vishnuvangala as is the case with most of the jira issues reported here the cause has been the jira collector not being correctly configured. Note that if you make a change to the collector config the change will only apply to newly collected jira items. Hence, you may need to wipe your jira data and recollect it.

sEstimate comes from the story point estimates that are put on stories. sEstimateTime comes from time estimates that are put on subtasks of stories. Hours estimates for tasks keep track of the total estimate and how much time has been put into the issue. From these open, wip, and done values can be deduced.

@Mahendra1260 double check your configuration. Note that if a sprint is not active (start date <= now <=(?) end date) it will not show up. If you do not select any team than "Any team" is assumed. MarkRx
277277346 @vishnuvangala The feature widget now has an option to display metrics based on the number of tickets instead of estimates. This is for setups that do not use estimates.

267035327 I'm not sure what jira v1000.621.2 is. It should be something like 5.x, 6.x, or 7.x.

To get estimates to show up your jira must be configured to have estimates on story points. There is no count of the number of issues currently - #940

You also need to make sure you configured the estimate fields
```properties
feature.jiraIssueTypeNames=Story
feature.jiraStoryPointsFieldName=customfield_10002
```
There are some trouble shooting steps listed in the readme here: https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/tree/master/collectors/feature/jira MarkRx

Updated Angular version to latest stable release of Angular (1.5.9), as well as updated version of UI-Bootstrap (2.3.0).  

Most of the changes that had to be made outside of the version changes revolved around Angular Bootstrap, and Angular Cookies. The bootstrap dependency started prefixing their modules with "uib", which accounts for a significant portion of the changes. Angular changed their cookie api to use "getters" and "puts" instead of accessing the variables directly.

266965934 Thanks @rob-miller-777 ,
    One quick question regarding git-lab is.. I dont see the widget getting updated automatically.. we are performing some commits on project and I have set the cron job property as 1min in my git-lab.properties file. But still I dont see them updated in widget.. Unless I click on edit and click on save.. then I'm able to see the updated results there.. any idea? vishnuvangala
267046759 If you refresh the page, do you see the new data?  The dashboard and the collector are on different timers.  So even if the collector retrieves new data, you won't see it on the dashboard until the dashboard refreshes what it has by calling the UI.  If you don't see the data when you refresh the page, but you do see it when you update the configuration of the widget, my guess would be that you are running into a bug I found.  It seems like there is an issue with all widgets where if you have the same widget running for the same data on multiple dashboards, and one dashboard is either deleted, or removes that widget, it will disable that widget on all dashboards that widget is on.  So for example in Gitlab, if DashboardA and DashboardB both have an SCM widget looking at GitlabRepo1.  If DashboardB is either deleted, or changes that widget to look at GitlabRepo2, it will also disable it for DashboardA.   rob-miller-777
266026226 I'm guessing you don't have the latest changes.  The port and protocol support was only merged into master 3 days ago.  Have you pulled the new code since then? rob-miller-777

266965934 Thanks @rob-miller-777 ,
    One quick question regarding git-lab is.. I dont see the widget getting updated automatically.. we are performing some commits on project and I have set the cron job property as 1min in my git-lab.properties file. But still I dont see them updated in widget.. Unless I click on edit and click on save.. then I'm able to see the updated results there.. any idea? vishnuvangala
267046759 If you refresh the page, do you see the new data?  The dashboard and the collector are on different timers.  So even if the collector retrieves new data, you won't see it on the dashboard until the dashboard refreshes what it has by calling the UI.  If you don't see the data when you refresh the page, but you do see it when you update the configuration of the widget, my guess would be that you are running into a bug I found.  It seems like there is an issue with all widgets where if you have the same widget running for the same data on multiple dashboards, and one dashboard is either deleted, or removes that widget, it will disable that widget on all dashboards that widget is on.  So for example in Gitlab, if DashboardA and DashboardB both have an SCM widget looking at GitlabRepo1.  If DashboardB is either deleted, or changes that widget to look at GitlabRepo2, it will also disable it for DashboardA.   rob-miller-777

column2: Fixes the dashboard sometimes not showing data right away due to a timing issue. I think it has to do with the order the asynchronous rest calls come back in. This wraps the setTeamData method into a $timeout function which puts it at the end of the event queue and causes a $scope.$apply() to be run after it is finished. I don't know if the $timeout wrap is necessary (as opposed to using $scope.$apply() but that is what other js functions do so I followed suit.

column2:
Added configurable pipeline stage names. Backwards compatible. Allows for more and different stage names. Also allows users to hide the Commit and Build stages.

Stage config defaults to:

> systemConfig.systemStages=${CONFIG_GLOBAL_SYSTEM_STAGES:-Commit,Build,DEV,QA,INT,PERF,PROD}

Assumptions:
- There is at most one "commit" stage and one "build" stage
- Users will not have more than 9 stages including build/commit (the UI column widths are not dynamic due to grids and I didn't see a need to make it dynamic)

![feature1100-2](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/17504314/20983884/21f0385c-bc8c-11e6-8dcd-6511a7c74e13.PNG)

![feature1100-3](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/17504314/20983890/282ebd06-bc8c-11e6-89b0-c5e169229f90.PNG)

![feature1100-4_2](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/17504314/20984086/e1412a04-bc8c-11e6-9c53-4c4b80d909e5.png)
column11: 278775942 Will try tomorrow. Thanks! MarkRx 279045840 I see a number of issues: - There are lingering references and logic referring to the System stages in the api settings. If any arbitrary stage can be created (as it seems is this case with the changes) then these need to be removed. If not then the UI needs to be tightened to make names of stages aliases to set system stages. - There needs to be a way of having deterministic ordering on environment stages. This is needed in pipeline computations (such as finding the last stage a pipeline was in). If the intent is to remove the set global system stages then you will have to store ordering in the widget. The code as it is right now is not going to properly compute pipeline metrics (the mappings map in the widget has no intrinsic ordering). You should not rely on using a specific implementation (LinkedHashMap) - I don't think getCommitsAfterStage was modified correctly. - My product dashboard is still computing based on the system stages set. If the intent is for any team to have any arbitrary stages then this needs to have some kind of computation to determine the stages to display MarkRx 282108959 @MarkRx - I pushed latest changes to branch https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/tree/pr-1020 . -> Removed instances of api systemConfig. -> Used the ordering for stages in sequence they are added. column2:
This PR creates a POST endpoint within the API that receives the data from Rundeck and creates an `EnvironmentComponent`.  The basic structure is a transformation from the Rundeck XML document that is provided to a `DeployDataCreateRequest` object, which can be passed into the existing create method.

This is dependent on existing PRs: #1005 and #1007 which are still under discussion.  I wanted to make this available so it could be reviewed and changes could be pushed up.

This is not a complete resolution for #1008 as I am working on a completely separate collector spring boot application that will be more flexible than this implementation.

column2:
When we serve the UI with gulp serve (without nginx), the interaction synchronization through [ghostMode](https://www.browsersync.io/docs/options#option-ghostMode) option causes problems. It is not working as intended and browsers end up in different pages sometimes and cause problems during testing. For example, we consistently end up in a scenario where one browser goes into a dashboard page whereas another browser remains in the home page (site.html), and eventually interactions trigger the deleteDashboard() javascript function on the latter browser. We consistently get a dashboard deleted when the Monitor widget's configure wheel button is clicked in the first browser. That is not the only case where dashboards get deleted though.

So the question is, was ghostMode intended to be used? If not, we could turn it off in gulpfile.js when initializing browser-sync, since it's causing the dashboards to be deleted during testing, which is rather annoying.

Other issues reporting similar problems: [#871](https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/issues/871), [#627](https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/issues/627)

@mrpudn @amitmawkin @tabladrum
column11:
265355983 `ghostMode` can be useful if you're demonstrating something with a teammate or something, but I agree that this functionality could be provided via a separate command (i.e. `npm run develop` or `gulp develop`) and turned off by default.

I don't think this would be terribly hard to implement, and changing the default behavior of `gulp serve` should be transparent to users. mrpudn
268127617 @mrpudn currently how to start Hygieia instance from gulp without ghost mode ? xpdable
268284806 I just created a PR to address this issue.

If it gets merged, ghost mode will be disabled, by default. To enable it, you will be able to run `gulp serve:ghost-mode`. mrpudn

column2: Merge new code 5/12/2016
These changes made for an easier process to add multiple Jenkins jobs to the dashboard

I have been working on a Rundeck collector which creates EnvironmentComponent deploy records.  I have a couple questions about the implementation:

1. I could use the Rundeck post-completion webhook to send records to a collector or build a collector from the API to run on a cron schedule, as the Github collector does. Is there a preferred approach?  Could I build the Rundeck post-completion webhook feature into the api itself, while also building a separate collector that runs on a cron schedule?
2. When building separate collectors, is it preferred to use the api endpoints to create mongo objects or do the collectors generally have their own `Repository` bean with a connection to the mongo db directly?

I created two PRs that I will be depending on for the implementation #1007 and #1005.  If these are not yet resolved, I would ask that we begin discussion there and then talk about the implementation here.

Adding #785 for reference.
